title: Why Every Great Idea Is a Remix ?
description:
If nothing is original, then what are we actually proud of?

This video breaks a deeply uncomfortable idea. That creativity is not invention, but rearrangement. That science does not move forward by creating something from nothing, but by compressing messy reality into simpler models.

We look at why the brain cannot imagine what it has never seen, why even genius is refinement rather than creation, and how figures like Newton and Einstein built their breakthroughs by filtering existing ideas, not inventing reality from scratch.

This is a continuation of ideas explored in our previous video, Mathematics of Creativity, where we showed how the mind recombines patterns instead of generating novelty out of thin air.

Nothing is original.
But not everything is meaningless.

The real skill is knowing what to keep, what to discard, and how to assemble ideas that matter.

title: Tri Dao: The End of Nvidia's Dominance, Why Inference Costs Fell & The Next 10X in Speed
description:
Tri Dao, Chief Scientist at Together AI and Princeton professor who created Flash Attention and Mamba, discusses how inference optimization has driven costs down 100x since ChatGPT's launch through memory optimization, sparsity advances, and hardware-software co-design. He predicts the AI hardware landscape will shift from Nvidia's current 90% dominance to a more diversified ecosystem within 2-3 years, as specialized chips emerge for distinct workload categories: low-latency agentic systems, high-throughput batch processing, and interactive chatbots. Dao shares his surprise at AI models becoming genuinely useful for expert-level work, making him 1.5x more productive at GPU kernel optimization through tools like Claude Code and O1. The conversation explores whether current transformer architectures can reach expert-level AI performance or if approaches like mixture of experts and state space models are necessary to achieve AGI at reasonable costs. Looking ahead, Dao sees another 10x cost reduction coming from continued hardware specialization, improved kernels, and architectural advances like ultra-sparse models, while emphasizing that the biggest challenge remains generating expert-level training data for domains lacking extensive internet coverage.

The question if human thought is a series of fixed processes that could be, in principle, imitated by a computer is a major theme of this lecture and, in Feynman's trademark style of teaching, gives us clear and yet very powerful answers for this field which has gone on to consume so much of our lives today.

description: Google has officially announced its return to smart glasses in 2026—and this time, it isn’t just chasing notifications. Project Aura is Google’s attempt to turn glasses into a real computing platform: a floating 70-degree virtual screen in front of your eyes that can run full Android apps in space, powered by Gemini’s vision. This video walks through the whole journey: how the original Google Glass collapsed under privacy backlash, overheating hardware, and the “Glasshole” stigma—and why the world of 2026 is finally ready for cameras and AR displays on faces. We break down Aura’s two versions (audio-only AI glasses and the full AR display model), show how hand tracking, eye tracking, and Circle to Search now extend into the real world, and explain why partnering with Warby Parker, Gentle Monster, Samsung, and XREAL might be the secret weapon that makes these glasses look and feel like normal eyewear instead of sci-fi props. We also dig into the hard questions: privacy indicators, social acceptance, and whether Aura slowly pulls dozens of daily interactions away from your phone until glasses become your main screen.
